      "code": "For two persons, the path = Manhattan distance iff we can find a monotone path along streets. This fails when:\n- Person A is on vertical street only (not on horizontal), Person B is on vertical street only, AND they're on different vertical streets. Because to get from one vertical street to another, you must use a horizontal street, but A must first travel to a horizontal street.\n\nWait: if A is at (x_i, y_A) on vertical street x_i (y_A not on any horizontal), and B is at (x_j, y_B) on vertical street x_j (y_B not on any horizontal), then to travel from A to B, A must go to some horizontal street y_h (either up or down), travel horizontally to x_j, then go to y_B. The cost is |y_A - y_h| + |x_i - x_j| + |y_h - y_B|. Minimum over y_h that is a horizontal street. This equals |x_i - x_j| + min over y_h of |y_A - y_h| + |y_h - y_B|. If there's a y_h between y_A and y_B, this equals |y_A - y_B|, so total = Manhattan. Otherwise it's more.\n\nSo it's inconvenient iff both are on vertical-only streets (different vertical streets) and no horizontal street exists between their y-coordinates. OR both on horizontal-only streets (different horizontal streets) and no vertical street between their x-coordinates.\n\nWhat if one is on vertical-only and other on horizontal-only? Person A at (x_i, y_A) vertical-only, Person B at (x_B, y_j) horizontal-only. Path: A goes to y_j (horizontal street), then to x_B. Cost = |y_A - y_j| + |x_i - x_B|. That equals Manhattan distance! So no inconvenience here.\n\nWhat about two persons on the same vertical street? They can travel directly, cost = |y_A - y_B| = Manhattan. Fine.\n\nSo the answer is:\n1. Count pairs of vertical-only persons on different vertical streets where no horizontal street y exists with min(y_A,y_B) < y < max(y_A,y_B) (strictly between).\n2. Count pairs of horizontal-only persons on different horizontal streets where no vertical street x exists strictly between their x-coordinates.\n\nFor case 1: vertical-only persons sorted by y. Two persons with y_A < y_B are inconvenient if there's no horizontal street strictly between y_A and y_B, i.e., the next horizontal street after y_A is >= y_B. This means they're in the same \"band\" between consecutive horizontal streets.\n\nSo: assign each vertical-only person to a band index (which interval between consecutive horizontal streets they fall in). Pairs in the same band on different vertical streets are inconvenient. If there are c_b persons in band b, the count is C(c_b, 2).\n\nSimilarly for horizontal-only persons in bands between vertical streets.\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nimport sys\nfrom bisect import bisect_left, bisect_right\ninput = sys.stdin.readline\n\ndef solve():\n    n, m, k = map(int, input().split())\n    xs = list(map(int, input().split()))\n    ys = list(map(int, input().split()))\n    xs_set = set(xs)\n    ys_set = set(ys)\n    \n    vert_only = []  # y-coords of persons on vertical street only\n    horiz_only = []  # x-coords of persons on horizontal street only\n    \n    for _ in range(k):\n        xp, yp = map(int, input().split())\n        on_vert = xp in xs_set\n        on_horiz = yp in ys_set\n        if on_vert and not on_horiz:\n            vert_only.append(yp)\n        elif on_horiz and not on_vert:\n            horiz_only.append(xp)\n    \n    ans = 0\n    # For vertical-only: band = index in ys intervals\n    from collections import defaultdict\n    band_count = defaultdict(int)\n    for yp in vert_only:\n        # band: which interval [ys[i], ys[i+1]] strictly inside\n        idx = bisect_right(ys, yp) - 1\n        band_count[idx] += 1\n    for c in band_count.values():\n        ans += c*(c-1)//2\n    \n    band_count2 = defaultdict(int)\n    for xp in horiz_only:\n        idx = bisect_right(xs, xp) - 1\n        band_count2[idx] += 1\n    for c in band_count2.values():\n        ans += c*(c-1)//2\n    \n    print(ans)\n\nt = int(input())\nfor _ in range(t):\n    solve()",
